fields.value: Korean Labor and Income Panel Study (KLIPS), 1998-2206: Wave 1-9 (M1194)

dsDescriptionValue.value: KLIPS is a longitudinal study, begun in 1998 of a representative sample of Korean households and individuals living in urban areas. The study is conducted annually to track the characteristics of households as well as the economic activities, labor movement, income, expenditures, education, job training, and social activities of individuals. Separate questionnaires are used for households and individuals. In wave 3 and 9, a youth questionnaire was added.  Topical modules include health and retirement (w4); old age (w6); working hours and leisure (w7); union and labor management relations (w8); types of employment (w10); and education (w11). More information is available from the Study Overview, downloadable from this site as a PDF. Much of the documentation, codebooks and questionnaires are in Korean language.

value: Urban areas nationwide, except Jeju Island. Incudes city sub-districts, towns and sub-counties
Households within the urban areas across the country, excluding Jeju Island.

fields.value: Sampling method used a two-stage stratified clustering sample.  First selection was made of enumeration districts (10%) and then selecting households.   The primary sampling units (PSU) consists of 21,675 enumeration districts and 19,025 enumeration districts were used as the sampling frame. Within each sampling unit 5-6 households were selected. Original sample beginning in year 1998 was 5000 households. All members of households age 15 years and older are included in the sample.

The household survey is conducted in face-to-face interviews with a household reference person or the spouse. All household members age 15 years and older are included in the individual survey. Most individual interviews are carried out face-to-face, but a small portion were interviewed by leaving and retrieving the questionnaire, or by telephone.
